Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) Notes

Retrieval-Augmented Generation, or RAG, is a technique that combines
information retrieval with text generation. Instead of relying purely
on the parametric knowledge stored in a language model's weights, a
RAG system first retrieves relevant chunks of text from an external
knowledge source, such as a document collection, and then feeds that
retrieved text to the language model as additional context before it
generates an answer.

The main motivation for RAG is to reduce hallucination and improve
factual accuracy. Language models can generate confident-sounding but
incorrect answers when they rely only on what they memorized during
training. By grounding the answer in retrieved, verifiable text, RAG
systems produce answers that are traceable back to a source document.

A typical RAG pipeline has several stages. First, documents are
ingested and converted into raw text. Second, the text is split into
smaller chunks, usually a few hundred words each, sometimes with
overlap between consecutive chunks so that context isn't lost at
chunk boundaries. Third, each chunk is converted into a vector
representation, called an embedding, using an embedding model.
Fourth, these embeddings are stored in a vector database that
supports fast similarity search.

When a user asks a question, the query itself is converted into an
embedding using the same embedding model. The vector database is then
searched to find the chunks whose embeddings are most similar to the
query embedding, typically using cosine similarity. The top-matching
chunks are retrieved and inserted into a prompt, along with the
original question, and passed to a language model. The language model
then generates a final answer, ideally using only the information in
the retrieved chunks.

There are several ways to improve a RAG system. Better chunking
strategies, such as splitting on semantic boundaries instead of a
fixed number of words, can improve retrieval quality. Using stronger
embedding models can capture semantic meaning more accurately, which
helps when the user's question uses different wording than the
document. Hybrid search, which combines keyword-based search (like
BM25 or TF-IDF) with dense vector search, often outperforms either
approach alone, especially for queries containing rare terms like
product names or IDs. Adding a re-ranking step after initial
retrieval, using a more powerful but slower model to re-score the top
candidates, can also significantly improve the relevance of the final
context passed to the language model.

RAG systems are widely used in chatbots, customer support assistants,
internal knowledge search tools, legal and medical document
assistants, and coding assistants that need to answer questions about
a specific private codebase. Because RAG does not require retraining
the language model itself, it is a relatively cheap and fast way to
adapt a general-purpose language model to a specific domain or a
private set of documents.
